---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";

const updated = "June 28, 2026";
---

<Base
  title="privacy policy - embody.tools"
  description="What embody.tools collects, why, the legal basis for it, and the rights you have over your data. A plain-language privacy policy for a small open-source project."
>
  <section class="page-section legal-hero">
    <p class="eyebrow">privacy</p>
    <h1>privacy policy</h1>
    <p class="lede">
      embody.tools is a small, open-source project. We collect as little as we can
      get away with, we don&rsquo;t sell anything, and there are no advertising
      trackers anywhere on this site. This page explains exactly what we keep, why
      we&rsquo;re allowed to keep it, and the rights you have over it.
    </p>
    <p class="legal-updated mono">Last updated: {updated}</p>
  </section>

  <article class="page-section tight legal-body">
    <h2>Who we are</h2>
    <p>
      embody.tools is operated by <strong>The Experiential Company, LLC</strong>
      (&ldquo;TEC,&rdquo; &ldquo;we,&rdquo; &ldquo;us&rdquo;), a California limited
      liability company, for the Embody &amp; Envoy open-source project. For
      data-protection purposes TEC is the <strong>data controller</strong> for this site. The site hosts
      the Collection &mdash; a gallery of transparent TouchDesigner networks (TDN)
      that anyone can inspect, copy, and remix. Questions about this policy, or any
      request about your data, can go to
      <a href="mailto:rosco@tec.design">rosco@tec.design</a>.
    </p>

    <h2>What we collect</h2>

    <h3>Account information</h3>
    <p>
      If you create an account, we store your email address, a display handle, an
      optional display name and bio, and a <strong>salted hash</strong> of your
      password &mdash; never the password itself. Authentication is handled by
      <a href="https://www.better-auth.com/">Better Auth</a>. If you instead sign in
      with GitHub, we receive only the basic profile fields GitHub returns (your
      account id, name, avatar URL, and the tokens needed to keep the session valid);
      we do not request access to your repositories or private data.
    </p>

    <h3>Sessions and cookies</h3>
    <p>
      When you sign in we set a strictly-functional session cookie so the site can
      recognize you on the next request. We record the session token, its
      expiry, and the IP address and user-agent string of the request that created
      it &mdash; standard fields used to keep sessions secure and let you sign out.
      We set <strong>no</strong> advertising or cross-site tracking cookies, and if
      you never sign in, no account or session data is created. The full breakdown is
      on the <a href="/cookies">cookie page</a>.
    </p>

    <h3>Content you contribute</h3>
    <p>
      When you publish a specimen, we store the TDN network you upload, a generated
      thumbnail, and the metadata you provide (title, description, category, license,
      and changelog notes). Contributed networks are scanned for capabilities and unsafe
      operators before they go live. Your handle is shown publicly as the
      <strong>attribution</strong> for anything you publish, and each version is kept
      as an immutable record so the history of a specimen stays diffable. Don&rsquo;t
      upload anything you wouldn&rsquo;t want public.
    </p>

    <h3 class="keep-case">Anti-abuse (Cloudflare Turnstile)</h3>
    <p>
      Contributing a specimen is protected by
      <a href="https://www.cloudflare.com/products/turnstile/">Cloudflare Turnstile</a>,
      a privacy-respecting CAPTCHA alternative that confirms you&rsquo;re a human
      without the puzzle grids. Turnstile runs a challenge in your browser and returns
      a token we verify server-side. Per Cloudflare, it is designed not to profile
      users or track them across sites. Sign-in and sign-up are rate-limited to
      deter automated abuse.
    </p>

    <h3>Analytics</h3>
    <p>
      We keep one kind of aggregate, non-identifying count: each specimen has a
      <strong>copy count</strong> that increments when anyone copies it &mdash; a
      total attached to the specimen, not to you. Beyond that, this site uses
      <a href="https://www.cloudflare.com/web-analytics/">Cloudflare Web Analytics</a>,
      a cookieless, privacy-first analytics tool that reports page-level traffic in
      aggregate. It does not fingerprint visitors, does not use client-side state, and
      collects no personal data. If the analytics token isn&rsquo;t configured for a
      given deployment, the beacon simply isn&rsquo;t loaded.
    </p>

    <h2>Where your data lives</h2>
    <p>
      The site runs on <a href="https://www.cloudflare.com/">Cloudflare</a>. Account
      and specimen metadata live in Cloudflare D1; uploaded TDN files and thumbnails
      live in Cloudflare R2; short-lived anti-abuse counters live in Cloudflare KV.
      Cloudflare acts as our infrastructure processor and may process request data
      (such as IP addresses) to deliver and protect the service. Optional account
      emails &mdash; verification and password resets &mdash; are sent through
      <a href="https://resend.com/">Resend</a> only when that service is configured
      for a deployment.
    </p>
    <p>
      TEC is based in the United States and Cloudflare is a global network, so your
      data may be <strong>stored or processed outside your own country</strong>,
      including in the United States. Where data is transferred out of the EU, UK, or
      Switzerland, our providers rely on recognized safeguards such as the Standard
      Contractual Clauses and the EU&ndash;U.S. Data Privacy Framework.
    </p>

    <h2>How we use it</h2>
    <p>
      We use the data above only to operate the service: to sign you in, to attribute
      and display the work you publish, to keep the site secure and free of spam and
      abuse, and to understand aggregate traffic so we can improve the project. We do
      <strong>not</strong> sell your data, and we don&rsquo;t share it with third
      parties except the infrastructure providers named here who process it on our
      behalf.
    </p>

    <h2>Why we&rsquo;re allowed to (legal basis)</h2>
    <p>
      Under the GDPR and similar laws we only process your data when we have a lawful
      basis for it. In plain terms:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>To run your account and publish your work</strong> &mdash; because
        it&rsquo;s necessary to provide the service you asked for. That&rsquo;s the
        contract formed by our <a href="/terms">Terms of Service</a>.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>To keep the site secure and free of abuse</strong>, and to understand
        aggregate traffic &mdash; because it&rsquo;s in our legitimate interest to run
        a safe, working service, weighed against your rights and freedoms.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>To meet legal obligations</strong> &mdash; for example, responding to a
        valid legal request or a copyright notice under our
        <a href="/dmca">DMCA policy</a>.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      We don&rsquo;t rely on consent for tracking, because there isn&rsquo;t any
      tracking &mdash; the only cookie we set is strictly necessary to sign you in.
    </p>

    <h2>How long we keep it</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Account data</strong> &mdash; until you delete your account, after
        which we remove it.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Sessions</strong> &mdash; until they expire or you sign out.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Published specimens</strong> &mdash; kept as an immutable, diffable
        history while published, and removed from the Collection on request (copies
        others already made under your chosen license stay theirs).
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Anti-abuse counters and IP-based rate-limit keys</strong> &mdash;
        ephemeral; they expire automatically within minutes.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Moderation reports</strong> &mdash; kept while we review them and for a
        reasonable period afterward as a record.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Your choices and your rights</h2>
    <p>
      You can browse the entire Collection without an account, and you can sign out at
      any time to end a session. If you do have an account, you have the right to:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Access</strong> a copy of the personal data we hold about you.</li>
      <li>
        <strong>Correct</strong> anything inaccurate &mdash; most profile fields you
        can edit yourself.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Delete</strong> your account and personal data (the &ldquo;right to
        erasure&rdquo;).
      </li>
      <li><strong>Export</strong> your data in a portable form.</li>
      <li>
        <strong>Restrict or object</strong> to processing, including anything we do on
        the basis of legitimate interest.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      To exercise any of these, email
      <a href="mailto:rosco@tec.design">rosco@tec.design</a> and we&rsquo;ll respond
      within 30 days. Note that published specimens may carry an open license (for
      example CC-BY-4.0) &mdash; copies others have already made under that license
      remain theirs to keep, but we will remove your authored entries on request.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>If you&rsquo;re in the EU, UK, or Switzerland</strong>, you also have the
      right to lodge a complaint with your local data-protection supervisory authority
      &mdash; though we&rsquo;d appreciate the chance to put things right first.
      <strong>If you&rsquo;re in California</strong>, you can ask us to access or delete
      your data, and for the record: we do not, and never will, sell or
      &ldquo;share&rdquo; your personal information.
    </p>

    <h2>Children</h2>
    <p>
      This site is not directed at children. You must be at least 13 to create an
      account, and where local law sets a higher age for consenting to online services
      (16 in parts of the EU), you must meet that age or have a parent or
      guardian&rsquo;s permission. We don&rsquo;t knowingly collect data from children
      below these ages; if you believe a child has created an account, contact us and
      we&rsquo;ll remove it.
    </p>

    <h2>Changes</h2>
    <p>
      We may update this policy as the project evolves. When we do, we&rsquo;ll change
      the &ldquo;last updated&rdquo; date above. Material changes will be noted in the
      project changelog.
    </p>

    <p class="legal-sign mono">
      See also the <a href="/terms">Terms of Service</a> and the
      <a href="/cookies">cookie page</a>.
    </p>
  </article>
</Base>
